[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In computer science and operations research, the **ant colony optimization** algorithm (**ACO**) is a probabilistic technique for solving computational problems that can be reduced to finding good paths through graphs.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial ants represent multi-agent methods inspired by the behavior of real ants.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone-based communication of biological ants is often the predominant paradigm used.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Combinations of artificial ants and local search algorithms have become a preferred method for numerous optimization tasks involving some sort of graph, e.g., vehicle routing and internet routing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] As an example, ant colony optimization is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial 'ants' (e.g. simulation agents) locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Real ants lay down pheromones to direct each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The simulated 'ants' similarly, record their positions and the quality of their solutions so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate better solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] One variation on this approach is the bees algorithm, which is more analogous to the foraging patterns of the honey bee, another social insect.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm is a member of the ant colony algorithms family, in swarm intelligence methods, and it constitutes some metaheuristic optimizations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Initially proposed by Marco Dorigo in 1992 in his PhD thesis, the first algorithm was aiming to search for an optimal path in a graph, based on the behavior of ants seeking a path between their colony and a source of food.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The original idea has since diversified to solve a wider class of numerical problems, and as a result, several problems have emerged, drawing on various aspects of the behavior of ants.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] From a broader perspective, ACO performs a model-based search and shares some similarities with estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the natural world, ants of some species (initially) wander randomly, and upon finding food return to their colony while laying down pheromone trails.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If other ants find such a path, they are likely to stop travelling at random and instead follow the trail, returning and reinforcing it if they eventually find food (see Ant communication).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Over time, however, the pheromone trail starts to evaporate, thus reducing its attractive strength.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The more time it takes for an ant to travel down the path and back again, the more time the pheromones have to evaporate.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A short path, by comparison, is marched over more frequently, and thus the pheromone density becomes higher on shorter paths than longer ones.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone evaporation also has the advantage of avoiding the convergence to a locally optimal solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If there were no evaporation at all, the paths chosen by the first ants would tend to be excessively attractive to the following ones.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In that case, the exploration of the solution space would be constrained.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The influence of pheromone evaporation in real ant systems is unclear, but it is very important in artificial systems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The overall result is that when one ant finds a good (i.e., short) path from the colony to a food source, other ants are more likely to follow that path, and positive feedback eventually leads to many ants following a single path.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The idea of the ant colony algorithm is to mimic this behavior with "simulated ants" walking around the graph representing the problem to be solved.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] New concepts are required since "intelligence" is no longer centralized but can be found throughout all minuscule objects.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Anthropocentric concepts have been known to lead to the production of IT systems in which data processing, control units and calculating power are centralized.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These centralized units have continually increased their performance and can be compared to the human brain.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The model of the brain has become the ultimate vision of computers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ambient networks of intelligent objects and, sooner or later, a new generation of information systems that are even more diffused and based on nanotechnology, will profoundly change this concept.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Small devices that can be compared to insects do not possess a high intelligence on their own.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Indeed, their intelligence can be classed as fairly limited.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is, for example, impossible to integrate a high performance calculator with the power to solve any kind of mathematical problem into a biochip that is implanted into the human body or integrated in an intelligent tag designed to trace commercial articles.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, once those objects are interconnected they develop a form of intelligence that can be compared to a colony of ants or bees.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the case of certain problems, this type of intelligence can be superior to the reasoning of a centralized system similar to the brain.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Nature offers several examples of how minuscule organisms, if they all follow the same basic rule, can create a form of collective intelligence on the macroscopic level.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of social insects perfectly illustrate this model which greatly differs from human societies.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This model is based on the cooperation of independent units with simple and unpredictable behavior.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through their surrounding area to carry out certain tasks and only possess a very limited amount of information to do so.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A colony of ants, for example, represents numerous qualities that can also be applied to a network of ambient objects.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of ants have a very high capacity to adapt themselves to changes in the environment, as well as great strength in dealing with situations where one individual fails to carry out a given task.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This kind of flexibility would also be very useful for mobile networks of objects which are perpetually developing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Parcels of information that move from a computer to a digital object behave in the same way as ants would do.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through the network and pass from one node to the next with the objective of arriving at their final destination as quickly as possible.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication is one of the most effective ways of communication which is widely observed in nature.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone is used by social insects such as bees, ants and termites; both for inter-agent and agent-swarm communications.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Due to its feasibility, artificial pheromones have been adopted in multi-robot and swarm robotic systems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication was implemented by different means such as chemical or physical (RFID tags, light, sound) ways.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, those implementations were not able to replicate all the aspects of pheromones as seen in nature.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Using projected light was presented in a 2007 IEEE paper by Garnier, Simon, et al. as an experimental setup to study pheromone-based communication with micro autonomous robots.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Another study presented a system in which pheromones were implemented via a horizontal LCD screen on which the robots moved, with the robots having downward facing light sensors to register the patterns beneath them.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the ant colony optimization algorithms, an artificial ant is a simple computational agent that searches for good solutions to a given optimization problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To apply an ant colony algorithm, the optimization problem needs to be converted into the problem of finding the shortest path on a weighted graph.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the first step of each iteration, each ant stochastically constructs a solution, i.e. the order in which the edges in the graph should be followed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the second step, the paths found by the different ants are compared.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The last step consists of updating the pheromone levels on each edge.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Each ant needs to construct a solution to move through the graph.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To select the next edge in its tour, an ant will consider the length of each edge available from its current position, as well as the corresponding pheromone level.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At each step of the algorithm, each ant moves from a state x to state y , corresponding to a more complete intermediate solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, each ant k computes a set $A_{k}(x)$ of feasible expansions to its current state in each iteration, and moves to one of these in probability.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The *trail level* represents a posteriori indication of the desirability of that move.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Trails are usually updated when all ants have completed their solution, increasing or decreasing the level of trails corresponding to moves that were part of "good" or "bad" solutions, respectively.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] where $L_{k}$ is the cost of the k th ant's tour (typically length) and Q is a constant.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Here are some of the most popular variations of ACO algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ant system is the first ACO algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm corresponds to the one presented above.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At the end of each iteration, only the best ant is allowed to update the trails by applying a modified global pheromone updating rule.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In this algorithm, the global best solution deposits pheromone on its trail after every iteration (even if this trail has not been revisited), along with all the other ants.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The elitist strategy has as its objective directing the search of all ants to construct a solution to contain links of the current best route.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm controls the maximum and minimum pheromone amounts on each trail.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only the global best tour or the iteration best tour are allowed to add pheromone to its trail.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To avoid stagnation of the search algorithm, the range of possible pheromone amounts on each trail is limited to an interval [τmax,τmin].
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All edges are initialized to τmax to force a higher exploration of solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The trails are reinitialized to τmax when nearing stagnation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All solutions are ranked according to their length.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only a fixed number of the best ants in this iteration are allowed to update their trials.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The amount of pheromone deposited is weighted for each solution, such that solutions with shorter paths deposit more pheromone than the solutions with longer paths.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An ant colony system (ACS) with communication strategies is developed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The artificial ants are partitioned into several groups.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Seven communication methods for updating the pheromone level between groups in ACS are proposed and work on the traveling salesman problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone deposit mechanism of COAC is to enable ants to search for solutions collaboratively and effectively.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] By using an orthogonal design method, ants in the feasible domain can explore their chosen regions rapidly and efficiently, with enhanced global search capability and accuracy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The orthogonal design method and the adaptive radius adjustment method can also be extended to other optimization algorithms for delivering wider advantages in solving practical problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is a recursive form of ant system which divides the whole search domain into several sub-domains and solves the objective on these subdomains.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The results from all the subdomains are compared and the best few of them are promoted for the next level.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The subdomains corresponding to the selected results are further subdivided and the process is repeated until an output of desired precision is obtained.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This method has been tested on ill-posed geophysical inversion problems and works well.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For some versions of the algorithm, it is possible to prove that it is convergent (i.e., it is able to find the global optimum in finite time).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first evidence of convergence for an ant colony algorithm was made in 2000, the graph-based ant system algorithm, and later on for the ACS and MMAS algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Like most metaheuristics, it is very difficult to estimate the theoretical speed of convergence.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In 2004, Zlochin and his colleagues showed that ACO-type algorithms are closely related to stochastic gradient descent, Cross-entropy method and estimation of distribution algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They proposed an umbrella term "Model-based search" to describe this class of metaheuristics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It has also been used to produce near-optimal solutions to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They have an advantage over simulated annealing and genetic algorithm approaches of similar problems when the graph may change dynamically; the ant colony algorithm can be run continuously and adapt to changes in real time.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This is of interest in network routing and urban transportation systems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first ACO algorithm was called the ant system and it was aimed to solve the travelling salesman problem, in which the goal is to find the shortest round-trip to link a series of cities.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The general algorithm is relatively simple and based on a set of ants, each making one of the possible round-trips along the cities.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] After each iteration, trails of pheromones evaporate.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To optimize the form of antennas, ant colony algorithms can be used.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ACO algorithm is used in image processing for image edge detection and edge linking.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The graph here is the 2-D image and the ants traverse from one pixel depositing pheromone.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The movement of ants from one pixel to another is directed by the local variation of the image's intensity values.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This movement causes the highest density of the pheromone to be deposited at the edges.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There are various methods to determine the heuristic matrix.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For the below example the heuristic matrix was calculated based on the local statistics: the local statistics at the pixel position $(i,j)$ .
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The parameter $\lambda$ in each of above functions adjusts the functions' respective shapes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Image edge detected using ACO: The images below are generated using different functions given by the equation (1) to (4).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] With an ACO algorithm, the shortest path in a graph, between two points A and B, is built from a combination of several paths.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is not easy to give a precise definition of what algorithm is or is not an ant colony, because the definition may vary according to the authors and uses.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Broadly speaking, ant colony algorithms are regarded as populated metaheuristics with each solution represented by an ant moving in the search space.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ants mark the best solutions and take account of previous markings to optimize their search.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They can be seen as probabilistic multi-agent algorithms using a probability distribution to make the transition between each iteration.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In their versions for combinatorial problems, they use an iterative construction of solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] According to some authors, the thing which distinguishes ACO algorithms from other relatives (such as algorithms to estimate the distribution or particle swarm optimization) is precisely their constructive aspect.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In combinatorial problems, it is possible that the best solution eventually be found, even though no ant would prove effective.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, in the example of the travelling salesman problem, it is not necessary that an ant actually travels the shortest route: the shortest route can be built from the strongest segments of the best solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, this definition can be problematic in the case of problems in real variables, where no structure of 'neighbours' exists.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The collective behaviour of social insects remains a source of inspiration for researchers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The wide variety of algorithms (for optimization or not) seeking self-organization in biological systems has led to the concept of "swarm intelligence", which is a very general framework in which ant colony algorithms fit.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There is in practice a large number of algorithms claiming to be "ant colonies", without always sharing the general framework of optimization by canonical ant colonies.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In practice, the use of an exchange of information between ants via the environment (a principle called "stigmergy") is deemed enough for an algorithm to belong to the class of ant colony algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This principle has led some authors to create the term "value" to organize methods and behavior based on search of food, sorting larvae, division of labour and cooperative transportation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These maintain a pool of solutions rather than just one.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The process of finding superior solutions mimics that of evolution, with solutions being combined or mutated to alter the pool of solutions, with solutions of inferior quality being discarded.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] that substitutes traditional reproduction operators by model-guided operators.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A related global optimization technique which traverses the search space by generating neighboring solutions of the current solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An inferior neighbor is accepted probabilistically based on the difference in quality and a temperature parameter.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The temperature parameter is modified as the algorithm progresses to alter the nature of the search.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Focuses on combining machine learning with optimization, by adding an internal feedback loop to self-tune the free parameters of an algorithm to the characteristics of the problem, of the instance, and of the local situation around the current solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Similar to simulated annealing in that both traverse the solution space by testing mutations of an individual solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] While simulated annealing generates only one mutated solution, tabu search generates many mutated solutions and moves to the solution with the lowest fitness of those generated.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To prevent cycling and encourage greater movement through the solution space, a tabu list is maintained of partial or complete solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is forbidden to move to a solution that contains elements of the tabu list, which is updated as the solution traverses the solution space.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A method that make use of clustering approach, extending the ACO.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An agent-based probabilistic global search and optimization technique best suited to problems where the objective function can be decomposed into multiple independent partial-functions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Chronology of ant colony optimization algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] In mathematical optimization, the **cutting-plane method** is any of a variety of optimization methods that iteratively refine a feasible set or objective function by means of linear inequalities, termed *cuts*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Such procedures are commonly used to find integer solutions to mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems, as well as to solve general, not necessarily differentiable convex optimization problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The use of cutting planes to solve MILP was introduced by Ralph E.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods for MILP work by solving a non-integer linear program, the linear relaxation of the given integer program.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The theory of Linear Programming dictates that under mild assumptions (if the linear program has an optimal solution, and if the feasible region does not contain a line), one can always find an extreme point or a corner point that is optimal.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The obtained optimum is tested for being an integer solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] If it is not, there is guaranteed to exist a linear inequality that *separates* the optimum from the convex hull of the true feasible set.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Finding such an inequality is the *separation problem*, and such an inequality is a *cut*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] A cut can be added to the relaxed linear program.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Then, the current non-integer solution is no longer feasible to the relaxation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This process is repeated until an optimal integer solution is found.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting-plane methods for general convex continuous optimization and variants are known under various names: Kelley's method, Kelley–Cheney–Goldstein method, and bundle methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] They are popularly used for non-differentiable convex minimization, where a convex objective function and its subgradient can be evaluated efficiently but usual gradient methods for differentiable optimization can not be used.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This situation is most typical for the concave maximization of Lagrangian dual functions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Another common situation is the application of the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition to a structured optimization problem in which formulations with an exponential number of variables are obtained.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Generating these variables on demand by means of delayed column generation is identical to performing a cutting plane on the respective dual problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting planes were proposed by Ralph Gomory in the 1950s as a method for solving integer programming and mixed-integer programming problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] However, most experts, including Gomory himself, considered them to be impractical due to numerical instability, as well as ineffective because many rounds of cuts were needed to make progress towards the solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Things turned around when in the mid-1990s Gérard Cornuéjols and co-workers showed them to be very effective in combination with branch-and-bound (called branch-and-cut) and ways to overcome numerical instabilities.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Nowadays, all commercial MILP solvers use Gomory cuts in one way or another.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Gomory cuts are very efficiently generated from a simplex tableau, whereas many other types of cuts are either expensive or even NP-hard to separate.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Among other general cuts for MILP, most notably lift-and-project dominates Gomory cuts.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] where A is a matrix and b , c is a vector.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The vector x is unknown and is to be found in order to maximize the objective while respecting the linear constraints.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The method proceeds by first dropping the requirement that the xi be integers and solving the associated relaxed linear programming problem to obtain a basic feasible solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Geometrically, this solution will be a vertex of the convex polytope consisting of all feasible points.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] If this vertex is not an integer point then the method finds a hyperplane with the vertex on one side and all feasible integer points on the other.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] This is then added as an additional linear constraint to exclude the vertex found, creating a modified linear program.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The new program is then solved and the process is repeated until an integer solution is found.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] where *xi* is a basic variable and the *xj'*s are the nonbasic variables (i.e. the basic solution which is an optimal solution to the relaxed linear program is $x_{i}={\bar {b}}_{i}$ and $x_{j}=0$ ).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] We write coefficients ${\bar {b}}_{i}$ and ${\bar {a}}_{i,j}$ with a bar to denote the last tableau produced by the simplex method.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] These coefficients are different from the coefficients in the matrix A and the vector b.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Consider now a basic variable $x_{i}$ which is not an integer.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] For any integer point in the feasible region, the left side is an integer since all the terms $x_{i}$ , $x_{j}$ , $\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor$ , $\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ are integers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The right side of this equation is strictly less than 1: indeed, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ is strictly less than 1 while $-\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Therefore the common value must be less than or equal to 0.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] must hold for any integer point in the feasible region.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] So the inequality above excludes the basic feasible solution and thus is a cut with the desired properties.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] More precisely, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor -\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative for any integer point in the feasible region, and strictly positive for the basic feasible (non integer) solution of the relaxed linear program.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods are also applicable in nonlinear programming.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/cutting-plane-method] The underlying principle is to approximate the feasible region of a nonlinear (convex) program by a finite set of closed half spaces and to solve a sequence of approximating linear programs.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A **genetic algorithm** (**GA**) is a metaheuristic inspired by the process of natural selection that belongs to the larger class of evolutionary algorithms (EA) in computer science and operations research.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are commonly used to generate high-quality solutions to optimization and search problems via biologically inspired operators such as selection, crossover, and mutation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Some examples of GA applications include optimizing decision trees for better performance, solving sudoku puzzles, hyperparameter optimization, and causal inference.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In a genetic algorithm, a population of candidate solutions (called individuals, creatures, organisms, or phenotypes) to an optimization problem is evolved toward better solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Each candidate solution has a set of properties (its chromosomes or genotype) which can be mutated and altered; traditionally, solutions are represented in binary as strings of 0s and 1s, but other encodings are also possible.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The evolution usually starts from a population of randomly generated individuals, and is an iterative process, with the population in each iteration called a *generation*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In each generation, the fitness of every individual in the population is evaluated; the fitness is usually the value of the objective function in the optimization problem being solved.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The more fit individuals are stochastically selected from the current population, and each individual's genome is modified (recombined and possibly randomly mutated) to form a new generation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The new generation of candidate solutions is then used in the next iteration of the algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Commonly, the algorithm terminates when either a maximum number of generations has been produced, or a satisfactory fitness level has been reached for the population.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] 2. a fitness function to evaluate the solution domain.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A standard representation of each candidate solution is as an array of bits (also called *bit set* or *bit string*).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Arrays of other types and structures can be used in essentially the same way.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The main property that makes these genetic representations convenient is that their parts are easily aligned due to their fixed size, which facilitates simple crossover operations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Variable length representations may also be used, but crossover implementation is more complex in this case.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Tree-like representations are explored in genetic programming and graph-form representations are explored in evolutionary programming; a mix of both linear chromosomes and trees is explored in gene expression programming.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Once the genetic representation and the fitness function are defined, a GA proceeds to initialize a population of solutions and then to improve it through repetitive application of the mutation, crossover, inversion and selection operators.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The population size depends on the nature of the problem, but typically contains hundreds or thousands of possible solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Often, the initial population is generated randomly, allowing the entire range of possible solutions (the search space).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Occasionally, the solutions may be "seeded" in areas where optimal solutions are likely to be found or the distribution of the sampling probability tuned to focus in those areas of greater interest.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] During each successive generation, a portion of the existing population is selected to reproduce for a new generation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Individual solutions are selected through a *fitness-based* process, where fitter solutions (as measured by a fitness function) are typically more likely to be selected.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Certain selection methods rate the fitness of each solution and preferentially select the best solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other methods rate only a random sample of the population, as the former process may be very time-consuming.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is defined over the genetic representation and measures the *quality* of the represented solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is always problem-dependent.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in the knapsack problem one wants to maximize the total value of objects that can be put in a knapsack of some fixed capacity.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A representation of a solution might be an array of bits, where each bit represents a different object, and the value of the bit (0 or 1) represents whether or not the object is in the knapsack.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Not every such representation is valid, as the size of objects may exceed the capacity of the knapsack.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The *fitness* of the solution is the sum of values of all objects in the knapsack if the representation is valid, or 0 otherwise.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The next step is to generate a second generation population of solutions from those selected, through a combination of genetic operators: crossover (also called recombination), and mutation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For each new solution to be produced, a pair of "parent" solutions is selected for breeding from the pool selected previously.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] By producing a "child" solution using the above methods of crossover and mutation, a new solution is created which typically shares many of the characteristics of its "parents".
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] New parents are selected for each new child, and the process continues until a new population of solutions of appropriate size is generated.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Although reproduction methods that are based on the use of two parents are more "biology inspired", some research suggests that more than two "parents" generate higher quality chromosomes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These processes ultimately result in the next generation population of chromosomes that is different from the initial generation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Generally, the average fitness will have increased by this procedure for the population, since only the best organisms from the first generation are selected for breeding, along with a small proportion of less fit solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These less fit solutions ensure genetic diversity within the genetic pool of the parents and therefore ensure the genetic diversity of the subsequent generation of children.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Opinion is divided over the importance of crossover versus mutation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] There are many references in Fogel (2006) that support the importance of mutation-based search.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] It is worth tuning parameters such as the mutation probability, crossover probability and population size to find reasonable settings for the problem's complexity class being worked on.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A very small mutation rate may lead to genetic drift (which is non-ergodic in nature).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A recombination rate that is too high may lead to premature convergence of the genetic algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A mutation rate that is too high may lead to loss of good solutions, unless elitist selection is employed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] An adequate population size ensures sufficient genetic diversity for the problem at hand, but can lead to a waste of computational resources if set to a value larger than required.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In addition to the main operators above, other heuristics may be employed to make the calculation faster or more robust.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The *speciation* heuristic penalizes crossover between candidate solutions that are too similar; this encourages population diversity and helps prevent premature convergence to a less optimal solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This generational process is repeated until a termination condition has been reached.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are simple to implement, but their behavior is difficult to understand.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In particular, it is difficult to understand why these algorithms frequently succeed at generating solutions of high fitness when applied to practical problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A hypothesis that a genetic algorithm performs adaptation by implicitly and efficiently implementing this heuristic.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] [crossed over], and resampled to form strings of potentially higher fitness.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In a way, by working with these particular schemata [the building blocks], we have reduced the complexity of our problem; instead of building high-performance strings by trying every conceivable combination, we construct better and better strings from the best partial solutions of past samplings".
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] "Because highly fit schemata of low defining length and low order play such an important role in the action of genetic algorithms, we have already given them a special name: building blocks.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Despite the lack of consensus regarding the validity of the building-block hypothesis, it has been consistently evaluated and used as reference throughout the years.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Many estimation of distribution algorithms, for example, have been proposed in an attempt to provide an environment in which the hypothesis would hold.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Although good results have been reported for some classes of problems, skepticism concerning the generality and/or practicality of the building-block hypothesis as an explanation for GAs' efficiency still remains.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Indeed, there is a reasonable amount of work that attempts to understand its limitations from the perspective of estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The simplest algorithm represents each chromosome as a bit string.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Typically, numeric parameters can be represented by integers, though it is possible to use floating point representations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The floating point representation is natural to evolution strategies and evolutionary programming.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The notion of real-valued genetic algorithms has been offered but is really a misnomer because it does not really represent the building block theory that was proposed by John Henry Holland in the 1970s.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This theory is not without support though, based on theoretical and experimental results (see below).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The basic algorithm performs crossover and mutation at the bit level.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other variants treat the chromosome as a list of numbers which are indexes into an instruction table, nodes in a linked list, hashes, objects, or any other imaginable data structure.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Crossover and mutation are performed so as to respect data element boundaries.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For most data types, specific variation operators can be designed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Different chromosomal data types seem to work better or worse for different specific problem domains.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] When bit-string representations of integers are used, Gray coding is often employed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In this way, small changes in the integer can be readily affected through mutations or crossovers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This has been found to help prevent premature convergence at so-called *Hamming walls*, in which too many simultaneous mutations (or crossover events) must occur in order to change the chromosome to a better solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other approaches involve using arrays of real-valued numbers instead of bit strings to represent chromosomes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Results from the theory of schemata suggest that in general the smaller the alphabet, the better the performance, but it was initially surprising to researchers that good results were obtained from using real-valued chromosomes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This was explained as the set of real values in a finite population of chromosomes as forming a *virtual alphabet* (when selection and recombination are dominant) with a much lower cardinality than would be expected from a floating point representation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] An expansion of the Genetic Algorithm accessible problem domain can be obtained through more complex encoding of the solution pools by concatenating several types of heterogenously encoded genes into one chromosome.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This particular approach allows for solving optimization problems that require vastly disparate definition domains for the problem parameters.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in problems of cascaded controller tuning, the internal loop controller structure can belong to a conventional regulator of three parameters, whereas the external loop could implement a linguistic controller (such as a fuzzy system) which has an inherently different description.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This particular form of encoding requires a specialized crossover mechanism that recombines the chromosome by section, and it is a useful tool for the modelling and simulation of complex adaptive systems, especially evolution processes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Another important expansion of the Genetic Algorithm (GA) accessible solution space was driven by the need to make representations amenable to variable levels of knowledge about the solution states.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Variable-length representations were inspired by the observation that, in nature, evolution tends to progress from simpler organisms to more complex ones—suggesting an underlying rationale for embracing flexible structures.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A second, more pragmatic motivation was that most real-world engineering and knowledge-based problems do not naturally conform to rigid knowledge structures.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] These early innovations in variable-length representations laid essential groundwork for the development of Genetic programming, which further extended the classical GA paradigm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Such representations required enhancements to the simplistic genetic operators used for fixed-length chromosomes, enabling the emergence of more sophisticated and adaptive GA models.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A practical variant of the general process of constructing a new population is to allow the best organism(s) from the current generation to carry over to the next, unaltered.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This strategy is known as *elitist selection* and guarantees that the solution quality obtained by the GA will not decrease from one generation to the next.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Parallel implementations of genetic algorithms come in two flavors.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Coarse-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume a population on each of the computer nodes and migration of individuals among the nodes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fine-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume an individual on each processor node which acts with neighboring individuals for selection and reproduction.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other variants, like genetic algorithms for online optimization problems, introduce time-dependence or noise in the fitness function.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms with adaptive parameters (adaptive genetic algorithms, AGAs) is another significant and promising variant of genetic algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The probabilities of crossover (pc) and mutation (pm) greatly determine the degree of solution accuracy and the convergence speed that genetic algorithms can obtain.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Researchers have analyzed GA convergence analytically.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Instead of using fixed values of *pc* and *pm*, AGAs utilize the population information in each generation and adaptively adjust the *pc* and *pm* in order to maintain the population diversity as well as to sustain the convergence capacity.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In AGA (adaptive genetic algorithm), the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on the fitness values of the solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] There are more examples of AGA variants: Successive zooming method is an early example of improving convergence.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In *CAGA* (clustering-based adaptive genetic algorithm), through the use of clustering analysis to judge the optimization states of the population, the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on these optimization states.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Recent approaches use more abstract variables for deciding *pc* and *pm*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Examples are dominance & co-dominance principles and LIGA (levelized interpolative genetic algorithm), which combines a flexible GA with modified A* search to tackle search space anisotropicity.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] It can be quite effective to combine GA with other optimization methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A GA tends to be quite good at finding generally good global solutions, but quite inefficient at finding the last few mutations to find the absolute optimum.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other techniques (such as simple hill climbing) are quite efficient at finding absolute optimum in a limited region.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Alternating GA and hill climbing can improve the efficiency of GA while overcoming the lack of robustness of hill climbing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This means that the rules of genetic variation may have a different meaning in the natural case.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] For instance – provided that steps are stored in consecutive order – crossing over may sum a number of steps from maternal DNA adding a number of steps from paternal DNA and so on.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] This is like adding vectors that more probably may follow a ridge in the phenotypic landscape.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Thus, the efficiency of the process may be increased by many orders of magnitude.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Moreover, the inversion operator has the opportunity to place steps in consecutive order or any other suitable order in favour of survival or efficiency.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A variation, where the population as a whole is evolved rather than its individual members, is known as gene pool recombination.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] A number of variations have been developed to attempt to improve performance of GAs on problems with a high degree of fitness epistasis, i.e. where the fitness of a solution consists of interacting subsets of its variables.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Such algorithms aim to learn (before exploiting) these beneficial phenotypic interactions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] As such, they are aligned with the Building Block Hypothesis in adaptively reducing disruptive recombination.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Prominent examples of this approach include the mGA, GEMGA and LLGA.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Problems which appear to be particularly appropriate for solution by genetic algorithms include timetabling and scheduling problems, and many scheduling software packages are based on GAs.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] GAs have also been applied to engineering.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are often applied as an approach to solve global optimization problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] As a general rule of thumb genetic algorithms might be useful in problem domains that have a complex fitness landscape as mixing, i.e., mutation in combination with crossover, is designed to move the population away from local optima that a traditional hill climbing algorithm might get stuck in.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Observe that commonly used crossover operators cannot change any uniform population.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Mutation alone can provide ergodicity of the overall genetic algorithm process (seen as a Markov chain).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In 1950, Alan Turing proposed a "learning machine" which would parallel the principles of evolution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Computer simulation of evolution started as early as in 1954 with the work of Nils Aall Barricelli, who was using the computer at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] His 1954 publication was not widely noticed.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Starting in 1957, the Australian quantitative geneticist Alex Fraser published a series of papers on simulation of artificial selection of organisms with multiple loci controlling a measurable trait.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] From these beginnings, computer simulation of evolution by biologists became more common in the early 1960s, and the methods were described in books by Fraser and Burnell (1970) and Crosby (1973).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fraser's simulations included all of the essential elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In addition, Hans-Joachim Bremermann published a series of papers in the 1960s that also adopted a population of solution to optimization problems, undergoing recombination, mutation, and selection.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Bremermann's research also included the elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Other noteworthy early pioneers include Richard Friedberg, George Friedman, and Michael Conrad.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Many early papers are reprinted by Fogel (1998).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Another approach was the evolutionary programming technique of Lawrence J.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Fogel, which was proposed for generating artificial intelligence.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary programming originally used finite state machines for predicting environments, and used variation and selection to optimize the predictive logics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms in particular became popular through the work of John Holland in the early 1970s, and particularly his book *Adaptation in Natural and Artificial Systems* (1975).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] His work originated with studies of cellular automata, conducted by Holland and his students at the University of Michigan.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Holland introduced a formalized framework for predicting the quality of the next generation, known as Holland's Schema Theorem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Research in GAs remained largely theoretical until the mid-1980s, when The First International Conference on Genetic Algorithms was held in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In the late 1980s, General Electric started selling the world's first genetic algorithm product, a mainframe-based toolkit designed for industrial processes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] In 1989, Axcelis, Inc. released Evolver,the world's first commercial GA product for desktop computers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] The New York Times technology writer John Markoff wrote about Evolver in 1990, and it remained the only interactive commercial genetic algorithm until 1995.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolver was sold to Palisade in 1997, translated into several languages, and is currently in its 6th version.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Since the 1990s, MATLAB has built in three derivative-free optimization heuristic algorithms (simulated annealing, particle swarm optimization, genetic algorithm) and two direct search algorithms (simplex search, pattern search).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary algorithms is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Swarm intelligence is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary computation is a sub-field of the metaheuristic methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/genetic-algorithm] Metaheuristic methods broadly fall within stochastic optimisation methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In the more general approach, an optimization problem consists of maximizing or minimizing a real function by systematically choosing input values from within an allowed set and computing the value of the function.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The generalization of optimization theory and techniques to other formulations constitutes a large area of applied mathematics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Such a formulation is called an **optimization problem** or a **mathematical programming problem** (a term not directly related to computer programming, but still in use for example in linear programming – see History below).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many real-world and theoretical problems may be modeled in this general framework.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] it suffices to solve only minimization problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] However, the opposite perspective of considering only maximization problems would be valid, too.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Problems formulated using this technique in the fields of physics may refer to the technique as *energy minimization*, speaking of the value of the function f as representing the energy of the system being modeled.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In machine learning, it is always necessary to continuously evaluate the quality of a data model by using a cost function where a minimum implies a set of possibly optimal parameters with an optimal (lowest) error.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Typically, A is some subset of the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , often specified by a set of *constraints*, equalities or inequalities that the members of A have to satisfy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The domain A of f is called the *search space* or the *choice set*, while the elements of A are called *candidate solutions* or *feasible solutions*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The function f is variously called an *objective function*, *criterion function*, *loss function*, *cost function* (minimization), *utility function* or *fitness function* (maximization), or, in certain fields, an *energy function* or *energy functional*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] A feasible solution that minimizes (or maximizes) the objective function is called an *optimal solution*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In mathematics, conventional optimization problems are usually stated in terms of minimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] that is to say, on some region around **x*** all of the function values are greater than or equal to the value at that element.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] While a local minimum is at least as good as any nearby elements, a global minimum is at least as good as every feasible element.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Generally, unless the objective function is convex in a minimization problem, there may be several local minima.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In a convex problem, if there is a local minimum that is interior (not on the edge of the set of feasible elements), it is also the global minimum, but a nonconvex problem may have more than one local minimum not all of which need be global minima.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Global optimization is the branch of applied mathematics and numerical analysis that is concerned with the development of deterministic algorithms that are capable of guaranteeing convergence in finite time to the actual optimal solution of a nonconvex problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often expressed with special notation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] This denotes the minimum value of the objective function *x*2 + 1, when choosing x from the set of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The minimum value in this case is 1, occurring at *x* = 0.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] asks for the maximum value of the objective function 2*x*, where x may be any real number.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, there is no such maximum as the objective function is unbounded, so the answer is "infinity" or "undefined".
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] This represents the value (or values) of the argument x in the interval (−∞,−1] that minimizes (or minimize) the objective function *x*2 + 1 (the actual minimum value of that function is not what the problem asks for).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the answer is *x* = −1, since *x* = 0 is infeasible, that is, it does not belong to the feasible set.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] represents the {*x*, *y*} pair (or pairs) that maximizes (or maximize) the value of the objective function *x* cos *y*, with the added constraint that x lie in the interval [−5,5] (again, the actual maximum value of the expression does not matter).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the solutions are the pairs of the form {5, 2*k*π} and {−5, (2*k* + 1)π}, where k ranges over all integers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Operators arg min and arg max are sometimes also written as argmin and argmax, and stand for *argument of the minimum* and *argument of the maximum*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Fermat and Lagrange found calculus-based formulae for identifying optima, while Newton and Gauss proposed iterative methods for moving towards an optimum.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The term "linear programming" for certain optimization cases was due to George B.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Dantzig, although much of the theory had been introduced by Leonid Kantorovich in 1939.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Adding more than one objective to an optimization problem adds complexity.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] For example, to optimize a structural design, one would desire a design that is both light and rigid.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] When two objectives conflict, a trade-off must be created.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] There may be one lightest design, one stiffest design, and an infinite number of designs that are some compromise of weight and rigidity.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The set of trade-off designs that improve upon one criterion at the expense of another is known as the Pareto set.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The curve created plotting weight against stiffness of the best designs is known as the Pareto frontier.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] A design is judged to be "Pareto optimal" (equivalently, "Pareto efficient" or in the Pareto set) if it is not dominated by any other design: If it is worse than another design in some respects and no better in any respect, then it is dominated and is not Pareto optimal.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The choice among "Pareto optimal" solutions to determine the "favorite solution" is delegated to the decision maker.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In other words, defining the problem as multi-objective optimization signals that some information is missing: desirable objectives are given but combinations of them are not rated relative to each other.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the missing information can be derived by interactive sessions with the decision maker.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Multi-objective optimization problems have been generalized further into vector optimization problems where the (partial) ordering is no longer given by the Pareto ordering.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often multi-modal; that is, they possess multiple good solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] They could all be globally good (same cost function value) or there could be a mix of globally good and locally good solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Obtaining all (or at least some of) the multiple solutions is the goal of a multi-modal optimizer.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Classical optimization techniques due to their iterative approach do not perform satisfactorily when they are used to obtain multiple solutions, since it is not guaranteed that different solutions will be obtained even with different starting points in multiple runs of the algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Common approaches to global optimization problems, where multiple local extrema may be present include evolutionary algorithms, Bayesian optimization and simulated annealing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The *satisfiability problem*, also called the *feasibility problem*, is just the problem of finding any feasible solution at all without regard to objective value.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] This can be regarded as the special case of mathematical optimization where the objective value is the same for every solution, and thus any solution is optimal.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many optimization algorithms need to start from a feasible point.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] One way to obtain such a point is to relax the feasibility conditions using a slack variable; with enough slack, any starting point is feasible.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Then, minimize that slack variable until the slack is null or negative.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The extreme value theorem of Karl Weierstrass states that a continuous real-valued function on a compact set attains its maximum and minimum value.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a lower semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its minimum; an upper semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its maximum point or view.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] One of Fermat's theorems states that optima of unconstrained problems are found at stationary points, where the first derivative or the gradient of the objective function is zero (see first derivative test).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, they may be found at critical points, where the first derivative or gradient of the objective function is zero or is undefined, or on the boundary of the choice set.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] An equation (or set of equations) stating that the first derivative(s) equal(s) zero at an interior optimum is called a 'first-order condition' or a set of first-order conditions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optima of equality-constrained problems can be found by the Lagrange multiplier method.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The optima of problems with equality and/or inequality constraints can be found using the 'Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions'.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] While the first derivative test identifies points that might be extrema, this test does not distinguish a point that is a minimum from one that is a maximum or one that is neither.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The conditions that distinguish maxima, or minima, from other stationary points are called 'second-order conditions' (see 'Second derivative test').
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] If a candidate solution satisfies the first-order conditions, then the satisfaction of the second-order conditions as well is sufficient to establish at least local optimality.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The envelope theorem describes how the value of an optimal solution changes when an underlying parameter changes.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The process of computing this change is called comparative statics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The maximum theorem of Claude Berge (1963) describes the continuity of an optimal solution as a function of underlying parameters.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] For unconstrained problems with twice-differentiable functions, some critical points can be found by finding the points where the gradient of the objective function is zero (that is, the stationary points).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a zero subgradient certifies that a local minimum has been found for minimization problems with convex functions and other locally Lipschitz functions, which meet in loss function minimization of the neural network.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The positive-negative momentum estimation lets to avoid the local minimum and converges at the objective function global minimum.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Constrained problems can often be transformed into unconstrained problems with the help of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Lagrangian relaxation can also provide approximate solutions to difficult constrained problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] When the objective function is a convex function, then any local minimum will also be a global minimum.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] There exist efficient numerical techniques for minimizing convex functions, such as interior-point methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, if the objective function is not a quadratic function, then many optimization methods use other methods to ensure that some subsequence of iterations converges to an optimal solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The first and still popular method for ensuring convergence relies on line searches, which optimize a function along one dimension.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] A second and increasingly popular method for ensuring convergence uses trust regions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Both line searches and trust regions are used in modern methods of non-differentiable optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Usually, a global optimizer is much slower than advanced local optimizers (such as BFGS), so often an efficient global optimizer can be constructed by starting the local optimizer from different starting points.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] To solve problems, researchers may use algorithms that terminate in a finite number of steps, or iterative methods that converge to a solution (on some specified class of problems), or heuristics that may provide approximate solutions to some problems (although their iterates need not converge).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The iterative methods used to solve problems of nonlinear programming differ according to whether they evaluate Hessians, gradients, or only function values.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] While evaluating Hessians (H) and gradients (G) improves the rate of convergence, for functions for which these quantities exist and vary sufficiently smoothly, such evaluations increase the computational complexity (or computational cost) of each iteration.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the computational complexity may be excessively high.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] One major criterion for optimizers is just the number of required function evaluations as this often is already a large computational effort, usually much more effort than within the optimizer itself, which mainly has to operate over the N variables.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The derivatives provide detailed information for such optimizers, but are even harder to calculate, e.g. approximating the gradient takes at least N+1 function evaluations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] For approximations of the 2nd derivatives (collected in the Hessian matrix), the number of function evaluations is in the order of N².
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Newton's method requires the 2nd-order derivatives, so for each iteration, the number of function calls is in the order of N², but for a simpler pure gradient optimizer it is only N.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] However, gradient optimizers need usually more iterations than Newton's algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Which one is best with respect to the number of function calls depends on the problem itself.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Besides (finitely terminating) algorithms and (convergent) iterative methods, there are heuristics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] A heuristic is any algorithm which is not guaranteed (mathematically) to find the solution, but which is nevertheless useful in certain practical situations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Also, the problem of computing contact forces can be done by solving a linear complementarity problem, which can also be viewed as a QP (quadratic programming) problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many design problems can also be expressed as optimization programs.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] This application is called design optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] One subset is the engineering optimization, and another recent and growing subset of this field is multidisciplinary design optimization, which, while useful in many problems, has in particular been applied to aerospace engineering problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] This approach may be applied in cosmology and astrophysics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Economics is closely enough linked to optimization of agents that an influential definition relatedly describes economics *qua* science as the "study of human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means" with alternative uses.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Modern optimization theory includes traditional optimization theory but also overlaps with game theory and the study of economic equilibria.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The *Journal of Economic Literature* codes classify mathematical programming, optimization techniques, and related topics under JEL:C61-C63.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] In microeconomics, the utility maximization problem and its dual problem, the expenditure minimization problem, are economic optimization problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Insofar as they behave consistently, consumers are assumed to maximize their utility, while firms are usually assumed to maximize their profit.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Also, agents are often modeled as being risk-averse, thereby preferring to avoid risk.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Asset prices are also modeled using optimization theory, though the underlying mathematics relies on optimizing stochastic processes rather than on static optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] International trade theory also uses optimization to explain trade patterns between nations.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The optimization of portfolios is an example of multi-objective optimization in economics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Since the 1970s, economists have modeled dynamic decisions over time using control theory.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] For example, dynamic search models are used to study labor-market behavior.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] A crucial distinction is between deterministic and stochastic models.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Macroeconomists build dynamic stochastic general equilibrium (DSGE) models that describe the dynamics of the whole economy as the result of the interdependent optimizing decisions of workers, consumers, investors, and governments.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Some common applications of optimization techniques in electrical engineering include active filter design, stray field reduction in superconducting magnetic energy storage systems, space mapping design of microwave structures, handset antennas, electromagnetics-based design.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Electromagnetically validated design optimization of microwave components and antennas has made extensive use of an appropriate physics-based or empirical surrogate model and space mapping methodologies since the discovery of space mapping in 1993.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are also used in power-flow analysis.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization has been widely used in civil engineering.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Construction management and transportation engineering are among the main branches of civil engineering that heavily rely on optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The most common civil engineering problems that are solved by optimization are cut and fill of roads, life-cycle analysis of structures and infrastructures, resource leveling, water resource allocation, traffic management and schedule optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Another field that uses optimization techniques extensively is operations research.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Operations research also uses stochastic modeling and simulation to support improved decision-making.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Increasingly, operations research uses stochastic programming to model dynamic decisions that adapt to events; such problems can be solved with large-scale optimization and stochastic optimization methods.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Mathematical optimization is used in much modern controller design.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] High-level controllers such as model predictive control (MPC) or real-time optimization (RTO) employ mathematical optimization.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] These algorithms run online and repeatedly determine values for decision variables, such as choke openings in a process plant, by iteratively solving a mathematical optimization problem including constraints and a model of the system to be controlled.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are regularly used in geophysical parameter estimation problems.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Given a set of geophysical measurements, e.g. seismic recordings, it is common to solve for the physical properties and geometrical shapes of the underlying rocks and fluids.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] The majority of problems in geophysics are nonlinear with both deterministic and stochastic methods being widely used.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear optimization methods are widely used in conformational analysis.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are used in many facets of computational systems biology such as model building, optimal experimental design, metabolic engineering, and synthetic biology.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Linear programming has been applied to calculate the maximal possible yields of fermentation products, and to infer gene regulatory networks from multiple microarray datasets as well as transcriptional regulatory networks from high-throughput data.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear programming has been used to analyze energy metabolism and has been applied to metabolic engineering and parameter estimation in biochemical pathways.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Similar techniques have been independently introduced on several occasions, including Pincus (1970), Khachaturyan et al.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 1983, this approach was used by Kirkpatrick, Gelatt Jr., and Vecchi for a solution of the traveling salesman problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] They also proposed its current name, simulated annealing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The name of the algorithm comes from annealing in metallurgy, a technique involving heating and controlled cooling of a material to alter its physical properties.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This notion of slow cooling implemented in the simulated annealing algorithm is interpreted as a slow decrease in the probability of accepting worse solutions as the solution space is explored.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Accepting worse solutions allows for a more extensive search for the global optimal solution.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Simulated annealing algorithms work by progressively decreasing the temperature from an initial positive value to zero.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] At each time step, the algorithm randomly selects a solution close to the current one, measures its quality, and moves to it according to the temperature-dependent probabilities of selecting better or worse solutions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The simulation can be performed either by a solution of kinetic equations for probability density functions, or by using a stochastic sampling method.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The method is an adaptation of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, a Monte Carlo method to generate sample states of a thermodynamic system, published by N.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The state *s* of some physical systems, and the function *E*(*s*) to be minimized, is analogous to the internal energy of the system in that state.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The goal is to bring the system, from an arbitrary *initial state*, to a state with the minimum possible energy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] At each step, the simulated annealing heuristic considers some neighboring state *s** of the current state *s*, and probabilistically decides between moving the system to state *s** or staying in state *s*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] These probabilities ultimately lead the system to move to states of lower energy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Typically, this step is repeated until the system reaches a state that is good enough for the application, or until a given computation budget has been exhausted.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Optimization of a solution involves evaluating the neighbor states, which are new states produced through conservatively altering the current state.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] For example, in the traveling salesman problem, each state is typically defined as a permutation of the cities to be visited, and the neighbors of any state are the set of permutations produced by swapping any two of these cities.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The well-defined way in which the states are altered to produce neighboring states is called a *move*, and different moves give different sets of neighboring states.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] These moves usually result in minimal alterations of the current state, in an attempt to progressively improve the solution through iteratively improving its parts (such as the city connections in the traveling salesman problem).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Metaheuristics use the neighbors of a solution as a way to explore the solution space, and although they prefer better neighbors, they probabilistically also accept worse neighbors to avoid getting stuck in local optima; they can find the global optimum if given enough time.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] States with a smaller energy are better than those with a greater energy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The probability function P must be positive even when $e_{\mathrm {new} }$ is greater than e .
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This feature prevents the method from becoming stuck at a local minimum that is worse than the global one.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] When T tends to zero, the probability $P(e,e_{\mathrm {new} },T)$ must tend to zero if $e_{\mathrm {new} }>e$ and to a positive value otherwise.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] For sufficiently small values of T , the system will then increasingly favor moves that go *downhill* (i.e., to lower energy values), and avoid those that go *uphill*.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] With $T=0$ the procedure reduces to the greedy algorithm, which makes only the downhill transitions.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the original description of simulated annealing, the probability $P(e,e_{\mathrm {new} },T)$ was equal to 1 when $e_{\mathrm {new} }<e$ —i.e., the procedure always moved downhill when it found a way to do so, irrespective of the temperature.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Many descriptions and implementations of simulated annealing still take this condition as part of the method's definition.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this condition is not essential for the method to work.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The P function is usually chosen so that the probability of accepting a move decreases when the difference $e_{\mathrm {new} }-e$ increases—that is, small uphill moves are more likely than large ones.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this requirement is not strictly necessary, provided that the above requirements are met.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Given these properties, the temperature T plays a crucial role in controlling the evolution of the state s of the system with regard to its sensitivity to the variations of system energies.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] To be precise, for a large T , the evolution of s is sensitive to coarser energy variations, while it is sensitive to finer energy variations when T is small.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Example illustrating the effect of cooling schedule on the performance of simulated annealing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] to attract at short range and repel at a slightly larger distance.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The elementary moves swap two adjacent pixels.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The name and inspiration of the algorithm demand controlled temperature variation.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This necessitates a gradual reduction of the temperature as the simulation proceeds.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The algorithm starts initially with T set to a high value, and then it is decreased at each step following some *annealing schedule*—which may be specified by the user but must end with $T=0$ towards the end of the allotted time budget.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] For any given finite problem, the probability that the simulated annealing algorithm terminates with a global optimal solution approaches 1 as the annealing schedule is extended.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This theoretical result, however, is not particularly helpful, since the time required to ensure a significant probability of success will usually exceed the time required for a complete search of the solution space.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The following pseudocode presents the simulated annealing heuristic as described above.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] It starts from a state *s*0 and continues until a maximum of *k*max steps have been taken.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the process, the call neighbour(*s*) should generate a randomly chosen neighbour of a given state s; the call random(0, 1) should pick and return a value in the range [0, 1], uniformly at random.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The annealing schedule is defined by the call temperature(*r*), which should yield the temperature to use, given the fraction r of the time budget that has been expended so far.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] These choices can have a significant impact on the method's effectiveness.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Unfortunately, there are no choices of these parameters that will be good for all problems, and there is no general way to find the best choices for a given problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The following sections give some general guidelines.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Simulated annealing may be modeled as a random walk on a search graph, whose vertices are all possible states, and the edges connecting the vertices are the candidate moves.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] An essential requirement for the neighbour() function is that it must provide a sufficiently short path on this graph from the initial state to any state that may be the global optimum – the diameter of the search graph must be small.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] To investigate the behavior of simulated annealing on a particular problem, it can be useful to consider the *transition probabilities* that result from the various design choices made in the implementation of the algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] For each edge $(s,s')$ of the search graph, the transition probability is defined as the probability that the simulated annealing algorithm will move to state $s'$ when its current state is s .
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This probability depends on the current temperature as specified by temperature(), on the order in which the candidate moves are generated by the neighbour() function, and on the acceptance probability function P().
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Note that the transition probability is **not** simply $P(e,e',T)$ , because the candidates are tested serially.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The specification of neighbour(), P(), and temperature() is partially redundant.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In practice, it's common to use the same acceptance function P() for many problems and adjust the other two functions according to the specific problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the formulation of the method by Kirkpatrick et al., the acceptance probability function $P(e,e',T)$ was defined as 1 if $e'<e$ , and $\exp(-(e'-e)/T)$ otherwise.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This formula was superficially justified by analogy with the transitions of a physical system; it corresponds to the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, in the case where T=1 and the proposal distribution of Metropolis–Hastings is symmetric.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] However, this acceptance probability is often used for simulated annealing even when the neighbour() function, which is analogous to the proposal distribution in Metropolis–Hastings, is not symmetric, or not probabilistic at all.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Nevertheless, most descriptions of simulated annealing assume the original acceptance function, which is probably hard-coded in many implementations of SA.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 1990, Moscato and Fontanari, and independently Dueck and Scheuer, proposed that a deterministic update (i.e. one that is not based on the probabilistic acceptance rule) could speed-up the optimization process without impacting on the final quality.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In 2001, Franz, Hoffmann and Salamon showed that the deterministic update strategy is indeed the optimal one within the large class of algorithms that simulate a random walk on the cost/energy landscape.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] When choosing the candidate generator `neighbour()`, one must consider that after a few iterations of the simulated annealing algorithm, the current state is expected to have much lower energy than a random state.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Therefore, as a general rule, one should skew the generator towards candidate moves where the energy of the destination state $s'$ is likely to be similar to that of the current state.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This heuristic (which is the main principle of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm) tends to exclude *very good* candidate moves as well as *very bad* ones; however, the former are usually much less common than the latter, so the heuristic is generally quite effective.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the traveling salesman problem above, for example, swapping two *consecutive* cities in a low-energy tour is expected to have a modest effect on its energy (length); whereas swapping two *arbitrary* cities is far more likely to increase its length than to decrease it.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Thus, the consecutive-swap neighbor generator is expected to perform better than the arbitrary-swap one, even though the latter could provide a somewhat shorter path to the optimum (with $n-1$ swaps, instead of $n(n-1)/2$ ).
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] A more precise statement of the heuristic is that one should try the first candidate states $s'$ for which $P(E(s),E(s'),T)$ is large.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] For the "standard" acceptance function P above, it means that $E(s')-E(s)$ is on the order of T or less.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Thus, in the traveling salesman example above, one could use a `neighbour()` function that swaps two random cities, where the probability of choosing a city-pair vanishes as their distance increases beyond T .
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] When choosing the candidate generator `neighbour()` one must also try to reduce the number of "deep" local minima—states (or sets of connected states) that have much lower energy than all its neighboring states.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] As a rule, it is impossible to design a candidate generator that will satisfy this goal and also prioritize candidates with similar energy.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] On the other hand, one can often vastly improve the efficiency of simulated annealing by relatively simple changes to the generator.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In this example, A and B lie in different "deep basins" if the generator performs only random pair-swaps; but they will be in the same basin if the generator performs random segment-flips.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The physical analogy that is used to justify simulated annealing assumes that the cooling rate is low enough for the probability distribution of the current state to be near thermodynamic equilibrium at all times.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Unfortunately, the *relaxation time*—the time one must wait for the equilibrium to be restored after a change in temperature—strongly depends on the "topography" of the energy function and on the current temperature.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] In the simulated annealing algorithm, the relaxation time also depends on the candidate generator, in a very complicated way.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Note that all these parameters are usually provided as black box functions to the simulated annealing algorithm.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Therefore, the ideal cooling rate cannot be determined beforehand and should be empirically adjusted for each problem.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Adaptive simulated annealing algorithms address this problem by connecting the cooling schedule to the search progress.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Other adaptive approaches such as Thermodynamic Simulated Annealing, automatically adjusts the temperature at each step based on the energy difference between the two states, according to the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Sometimes it is better to move back to a solution that was significantly better rather than always moving from the current state.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] This process is called *restarting* of simulated annealing.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] To do this we set s and e to ${\text{sbest}}$ and ${\text{ebest}}$ and perhaps restart the annealing schedule.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] The decision to restart could be based on several criteria.
[src:metaheuristic-optimization/simulated-annealing] Notable among these include restarting based on a fixed number of steps, based on whether the current energy is too high compared to the best energy obtained so far, restarting randomly, etc.
